.RE
.B
\fBresponse_timeout() :: timeout() | {abs, integer()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Response time-out for an asynchronous call.

.PP
Used to set a time limit on how long to wait for a response using either \fIreceive_response/2\fR, \fIreceive_response/3\fR, \fIwait_response/2\fR, or \fIwait_response/3\fR. The time unit used is \fImillisecond\fR. Currently valid values:

0..4294967295
.RS 2
Timeout relative to current time in milliseconds.


.RE

infinity
.RS 2
Infinite timeout. That is, the operation will never time out.


.RE

{abs, Timeout}
.RS 2
An absolute Erlang monotonic time timeout in milliseconds.  That is, the operation will time out when 
\fIerlang:monotonic_time(millisecond)\fR returns a value larger than or equal to \fITimeout\fR. \fITimeout\fR is not allowed to identify a time further into the future than \fI4294967295\fR milliseconds. Identifying the timeout using an absolute timeout value is especially handy when you have a deadline for responses corresponding to a complete collection of requests (\fIrequest_id_collection/0\fR) , since you do not have to recalculate the relative time until the deadline over and over again.

.RE


